# Introduction

The book describes challenges associated with building highly scalable distributed web applications solutions for overcoming the challenges then describes steps to building a modern web application.

The intent of the book is not to be a comprehensive guide and instead to give the reader enough content to allow building of an application plus pointers for the reader to also continue with their inquiry.

# Birth of the Web

## Web

In 1998, At CERN, Sir Tim Berners-Lee, invented the Web so that information could be shared by Scientists.

The use of the internet started growing exponentially.

## Web Scalability

Due to the exponential growth of the web, scalability became an issue that needed urgent attention.

In 1993, Roy Fielding became actively involved with the World Wide Web and in early 1994, got involved with specifying and improving the WWW infrastructure, URI, HTTP and HTML.

In 2000, Roy Fielding submitted his dissertation on Architectural Styles and the design of Network based Software Architecture. The dissertation detailed the Representational State Transfer (REST) Architectural Style for developing scalable distributed network based software systems.

# What is REST?

REST is a set of architectural constraints which allow web applications to scale. 

The constraints are client-server architecture, layered system, stateless, cache, uniform interface, code-on-demand.

## Client-Server Architecture

The client-server architecture constraint requires a central server service request from many clients.  

One of the advantages of the architecture is that the system can be scaled as demand increases. 

Scaling can be done by adding new servers (horizontal scaling) or  increasing the server resource like CPU and memory (vertical scaling).

## Layered System

The layered system constraint provides separation of concerns between the system boundaries allowing the system to be easily developed, maintained and scaled depending on demand.

The diagram shows the presentation, business and data layers. The layers are in a hierarchical order. 

The presentation layer is at the top and is responsible for UIs and user interaction.  
The business layer is where the business rules are applied.  
The data layer is where the application data is stored.

## Stateless

The stateless constraint requires the request to contain all the information required for the server to generate the response. 

This constraint allows the server to service many requests from clients since the server does not track client’s state between requests.

## Cache

The cache constraints require responses to be labeled so that the client or intermediaries can cache the result and use it for subsequent requests instead of making a new request to the server.

Caching improves network efficiency as requests to the server is reduced.

## Uniform Interface

In REST, data is moved from the storage location to the client’s location. The client can then process and render the data as required.

The uniform Interface constraint requires the standardisation of how the data is accessed and manipulated.
